2 Amtrak workers killed when train strikes backhoe
Chester, Pennsylvania (CNN)Amtrak said Monday it will restore service, albeit with some delays, along the route where one of its trains carrying 341 passengers crashed into a backhoe the day before.
"We're still gathering the facts," said Ryan Frigo, the National Transportation Safety Board official in charge of investigating the crash, which killed two people.
Here's a look at what we know -- and don't know -- so far:
NTSB officials will be looking at multiple factors that may have played into the crash: mechanical, operations, signal, track, human performance and survival.
Frigo said that the event data recorder and forward-facing and inward-facing video from the locomotive have been recovered.
The big unanswered questions: Why was the backhoe on the track near Chester, just south of Philadelphia? Why did the train continue its route from New York to Savannah, Georgia, when Amtrak construction workers may have been on the track?
The two people killed were construction workers for the railroad service, a source close to the investigation said. Sen. Chuck Schumer, D-New York, said the two people killed were the backhoe operator and his supervisor, both Amtrak employees.
The train was carrying about 341 passengers and seven crew members when it crashed, Amtrak said. The impact caused the lead engine of the train to derail.
